The paper deals with a distributed algorithm for scheduling on graph networks, which involves communication and coordination between processors. This suggests that the paper belongs to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also deals with network routing and scheduling, which suggests that it could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper involves the selection of paths and the use of graph algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also involves the design and analysis of approximation algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the Algorithms (cs.AL) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of competition and profit maximization, which suggests that it could belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category.
